quotation: robert merton, jr. and myron scholes were founding partners in the large speculative trading firm called long-term capital management, or ltcm?it was a collection of people with top-knotch resumes, from the highest ranks of academia. they were considered geniuses. the ideas of portfolio theory inspired their risk management of possible outcomes-thanks to their sophisticated `calculations' . they managed to enlarge the ludic fallacy to industrial proportions. then, during the summer of 1998, a combination of large events, triggered by a russian financial crisis, took place that lay outside their models. it was a black swan. ltcm went bust and almost took down the entire financial system with it, as the exposures were massive. since their models ruled out the possibility of large deviations, they allowed themselves to take a monstrous amount of risk. the ideas of merton and scholes, as well as those of modern portfolio theory, were starting to go bust. the magnitude of the losses was spectacular, too spectacular to allow us to ignore the intellectual comedy. many friends and i thought that the portfolio theorists would suffer the fate of tobacco companies: they were endangering people's savings and would soon be brought to account for the consequences of their gaussian-inspired methods. none of that happpened. instead, mba's went on learning portfolio theory.

quotation: A black swan event has three key elements. First, it must be rare-like a million-to-one chance of something happening. It must have an extreme impact-much like September 11th changed many Americans, or a tsunami or earthquake that eliminates a major city. Lastly, real black swans are impossible to predict-yet using the wisdom of 20/20 hindsight, they will have shown signs of predictability though those signs were incomprehensible prior to the event. But there's another colored swan - the gray swan. It's a cousin to the black swan. It, too, is rare. It, too, can have an extreme impact. But its key differentiation is that, unlike a true black swan, the gray swan is predictable-though those who predict them are often cast aside and thought to be well outside of mainstream thinking. Identifying and analyzing the risk of gray swan events is something that is core to our investment philosophy. In the current market environment-stocks hitting new highs almost daily, debt at historic levels, interest rates at historic lows-gray swans deserve attention. They hold the great potential of doing great damage if and when one or more of them land. Right now, we see an entire flock of gray swans circling the global economy. Each has the potential to dramatically change the financial landscape.
speaker: Chuck Butler
